(184, 2, '2011-07-21 21:45:58', '2011-07-22 04:45:58', 'A California Court of Appeals judge once described the Small Claims Courts (limited to claims of $7,500.00 dollars or less) in our State, as a judicial forum yielding “speedy common sense justice without the need to resort to lawyers.” Indeed, the Small Claims Courts provide several benefits not generally offered by Courts of Limited (claims above $7,500.00 dollars but less than $25,000.00 dollars) and Unlimited (claims above $25,000.00 dollars) jurisdiction.\n\nThose benefits include, but are not limited to, the following:\n<ol>\n	<li><span style="text-decoration: underline">Quick Resolution</span>– Small Claims matters are generally resolved within two or three months from the date that the Plaintiff (individual initiating the lawsuit) files his or her complaint (document that sets forth the Plaintiff’s claims and request for relief, usually money). This is very different than the filing of a lawsuit in Limited or Unlimited Civil Jurisdiction, which, potentially, can go on for a year or two, sometimes even longer;</li>\n	<li><span style="text-decoration: underline">Affordable</span> – The cost for the filing of the complaint varies depending on the amount of your claim. Filing fees start at thirty dollars and cap out at seventy-five dollars.  Additionally, attorneys cannot represent litigating parties (Plaintiff or Defendant) in Small Claims court. So, a litigating party can get their day in court without the expense of retaining a lawyer and, thus, making the Small Claims forum even more affordable. Win-win.</li>\n	<li><span style="text-decoration: underline">Preservation of Judicial Resource</span>s– The courtrooms dealing with Limited and Unlimited Civil matters, especially, in Los Angeles County (the largest trial court system in the United States), are simply swamped with heavy caseloads. In addition, in 2010, the County laid off over three hundred court employees, and implemented a monthly furlough day for an entire year, causing even more delays in resolving these matters.  Simply put, more cases, less courtroom staff and time to handle these matters equals longer periods of time before outcome resolution. As such, Small Claims Courts play a critical role in alleviating Limited and Unlimited courtrooms of matters that can be handled by a judge in a speedy and fair manner.</li>\n</ol>\nAs you can see, the Small Claims Courts provide a tremendous public interest by providing us with an opportunity to resolve our grievances with little expense and delays. However, there are some perils in selecting the Small Claims judicial forum.  Chiefly among these dangers is the selection of the wrong forum.\n\nAs I mentioned above, Small Claims Courts can only handle matters in which litigating parties are seeking $7<ins datetime="2011-06-21T22:05" cite="mailto:raindeo">,</ins>500 dollars or less in damages.  What happens if your matter is worth more than this amount, but you, nevertheless, file in and are successful in obtaining a judgment in Small Claims Court?<ins datetime="2011-06-21T21:56" cite="mailto:raindeo"> </ins>\n\nRegretfully, you are more than likely limited to the amount of your judgment, which can be pretty painful as the example below will demonstrate.\n\nI recently heard of a situation in which a litigating party, who speaks only Spanish and who has no legal background or education, filed a matter in Small Claims Court.  She alleged that a contractor had breached a contract and performed less than workmanlike craftsmanship on her home.  She paid him approximately $80,000.00 dollars to perform the construction, which he did not complete.  She had independent evidence that the work performed was shoddy, below the proper construction standard, and that it would cost her over $100,000.00 dollars to get what she initially bargained for – an acceptable addition to her home.\n\nThe judge ruled in her favor, and entered into a judgment against the contractor in the amount of $7<ins datetime="2011-06-21T21:58" cite="mailto:raindeo">,</ins>500.00 dollars even though she would have more than likely obtained a much, much larger judgment if she would filed in a judicial forum with no limitations on damages.\n\nYou must be wondering why this lady is precluded from re-filing her matter in a different judicial forum for the purpose of obtaining larger damages?  The law in California, and in most states, has a legal concept akin to the old adage – you only get one bite at the proverbial apple.  This concept is called <em>Res Judacata</em>, and this Latin principal stands for preventing the same litigating parties from re-filing their same claims in subsequent litigation.\n\nIn the instant matter, this principal seems rather harsh and unsympathetic to the lady mentioned above; however, you can imagine what would happen if this law was not in place.  Indeed, litigating parties who lost their respective lawsuits, or who did not obtain the damages amount they wanted, would simply go to another court and re-file their lawsuits.\n\nThis ability to go shopping for different courtrooms until you found one that ruled the way you wanted is simply unacceptable, and would be an absolute nightmare for our court system, and the litigating party on the other end of the lawsuit.  He or she would never know if the problem central to the lawsuit would ever go away.  Lawsuits should have a beginning and an end, and <em>Res Judacata</em> make sure that they do.\n\nNext time you have a potential lawsuit, think twice about where is the best judicial forum to file it in.  Also, in some instances, you should consult with an attorney if you are unsure about where you should proceed with your lawsuit.  Remember, the Small Claims Courts can be the right place for you and your lawsuit, or it can be the absolute wrong place, too.\n\nIf you have any questions regarding this article, or questions regarding litigation counseling, please do not hesitate to contact the Law Offices of Omar S. Anorga to discuss.  Our telephone number is 213 489-1271, email address <a href="mailto:omar@anorgalaw.com">omar@anorgalaw.com</a>, and website Anorgalaw.com.  Also, if you would like more information about Small Claims Court, please visit this informative self-help website: <a href="http://www.courtinfo.ca.gov/selfhelp/smallclaims/">http://www.courtinfo.ca.gov/selfhelp/smallclaims/</a>', 'The Joys and Pains of Small Claims Court', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-joys-and-pains-of-small-claims-court', '', '', '2014-11-05 17:51:18', '2014-11-05 17:51:18', '', 0, 'http://anorgalaw.com/blog/?p=64', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(185, 2, '2012-06-28 11:48:38', '2012-06-28 18:48:38', '\r\n<p>I recently received an email from a client who had these kind words to say:</p>\r\n<p>“Thank you for all you have done so far, it’s always a pleasure to work with someone as dedicated and efficient as yourself.”</p>\r\n<p>Ramona O. Novelo – Owner of Sunrise Home Care, Inc</p>\r\n', 'Client Testimonial ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'client-testimonial', '', '', '2014-11-05 17:51:18', '2014-11-05 17:51:18', '', 0, 'http://anorgalaw.com/blog/?p=83', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(186, 1, '2013-03-26 06:26:30', '2013-03-26 06:26:30', '<h2 class="category-title">Blog</h2>\n<div class="rssfeed">\n\n[rss feed="http://anorgalaw.com/blog/feed/" num="5" excerpt="true" target="_blank"]\n</div>', 'BLOG', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '83-revision', '', '', '2013-03-26 06:26:30', '2013-03-26 06:26:30', '', 83, 'http://anorgalaw.com/83-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(187, 1, '2012-09-20 14:00:41', '2012-09-20 21:00:41', 'As an attorney representing both emerging and established businesses, more often than not, I am frequently counseling them about the benefits of protecting their intellectual property.  For some, it’s a copyright, or a patent, and for most, it’s either a trade secret or a trademark.  My practice does not include counseling on copyrights or patents, and we have already discussed trade secrets in this newsletter, so, let us briefly focus in on trademarks.\n\nWhat is a trademark? There are several definitions of a trademark, but I like this one: “A <em>trademark </em>is a word, name, symbol, device, or any combination thereof used to identify and distinguish a good.”  So, think about your favorite soft drink.  For some its, COKE, and for others, its PEPSI.  I tend to like SQUIRT over both of these sodas.  Nevertheless, the point, however, is that each of these soft drinks are prime examples of words being used to describe a tangible good that is different from similar tangible goods.\n\nMore often than not, people innocently and mistakenly use the word trademark interchangeably with other types of marks – like, a <em>service mark</em>, which is a mark used to describe and identify the source of a service – like JIFFY LUBE or ROTOR ROOTER, which provide services, and NOT tangible goods.  Other examples of “trademarks” include,  a <em>certification mark</em> – think ENERGY STAR as seen on certain appliances; or a <em>collective mark</em> – think GIRLS SCOUTS or CPAs.  And, sometimes <em>slogans, shapes, or colors</em> get “trademark” protection.  So, think of Nike’s Just Do It slogan, or the shape of Coke’s glass soda bottle, or McDonald’s use of the colors red and yellow in their restaurants.\n\nA quick commercial break - for brevity purposes, we will continue to use the word trademark to describe the different marks mentioned above even though you should know that the using the word trademark, in some instances, might not be technically correct.\n\nTechnicalities aside, an underlining issue for all these trademarks, is usage.\n\nProtection of trademarks depends upon, and begins with, <span style="text-decoration: underline">actual use of the mark in commerce</span>. Trademark protection is available under the common law from the time that the owner begins to use the trademark in commerce.  However, further protection may be obtained by federally registering the trademark; the fact remains – you get NO protection if you are NOT using the trademark.\n\nThe federal registration process is rather straightforward.  Let’s briefly discuss the process of getting your trademark registered through the Patent and Trademark Office (PTO), which is responsible for the federal registration of trademarks.\n\nWhen an application is received, the PTO reviews it to determine if it meets the minimum requirements for receiving a filing date. If the application meets the filing requirements, the PTO assigns it a serial number and sends the applicant a receipt about two months after filing.  About four months after filing, an examining attorney at the PTO reviews the application and determines whether the mark may be registered.  The examiner will reject an application for several reasons; however, a common ground for refusal is likelihood of confusion between the applicant\'s trademark and existing registered trademark.\n\nIf the application is not rejected, then the examiner will approve the trademark for publication in the Official Gazette, a weekly publication of the PTO.  If there is no opposition to the publication, the trademark will finally be considered registered, and the examining attorney will issue a certificate of registration.\n\nIndeed, getting your trademark federally registered is beneficial for several reasons, however, the primary reason to do so is that your trademark will have nation-wide trademark protection.  As opposed to using your trademark without registration, which will limit your trademark protection to your geographical area.  So, your exterminating business with the name Vamanos Pest would more than likely only have trademark protection in your city, maybe county.  It is highly unlikely, in a big state like California, for example, that you could prevent someone in San Francisco from using your trademark, Vamanos Pest, if you are operating the same in San Diego.\n\nAs you can imagine, there is a lot more to trademarks than what we have discussed herein.  I only have so much space.  Nevertheless, you should walk away knowing that: 1) trademarks vary in type; 2) you have to use them in commerce; and 3) it’s probably best that you have them federally registered.  If you have any questions regarding trademarks, or if you would like to have a trademark registered, please do not hesitate to contact us.', 'Trademark - What is it?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '94-revision', '', '', '2012-09-20 14:00:41', '2012-09-20 21:00:41', '', 94, 'http://anorgalaw.com/94-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2013-04-24 02:11:37', '2013-04-24 02:11:37', '\r\n<p>As an attorney representing both emerging and established businesses, more often than not, I am frequently counseling them about the benefits of protecting their intellectual property.  For some, it’s a copyright, or a patent, and for most, it’s either a trade secret or a trademark.  My practice does not include counseling on copyrights or patents, and we have already discussed trade secrets in this newsletter, so, let us briefly focus in on trademarks.</p>\r\n<p>What is a trademark? There are several definitions of a trademark, but I like this one: “A &lt;em&gt;trademark &lt;/em&gt;is a word, name, symbol, device, or any combination thereof used to identify and distinguish a good.”  So, think about your favorite soft drink.  For some its, COKE, and for others, its PEPSI.  I tend to like SQUIRT over both of these sodas.  Nevertheless, the point, however, is that each of these soft drinks are prime examples of words being used to describe a tangible good that is different from similar tangible goods.</p>\r\n<p>More often than not, people innocently and mistakenly use the word trademark interchangeably with other types of marks – like, a &lt;em&gt;service mark&lt;/em&gt;, which is a mark used to describe and identify the source of a service – like JIFFY LUBE or ROTOR ROOTER, which provide services, and NOT tangible goods.  Other examples of “trademarks” include,  a &lt;em&gt;certification mark&lt;/em&gt; – think ENERGY STAR as seen on certain appliances; or a &lt;em&gt;collective mark&lt;/em&gt; – think GIRLS SCOUTS or CPAs.  And, sometimes &lt;em&gt;slogans, shapes, or colors&lt;/em&gt; get “trademark” protection.  So, think of Nike’s Just Do It slogan, or the shape of Coke’s glass soda bottle, or McDonald’s use of the colors red and yellow in their restaurants.</p>\r\n<p>A quick commercial break - for brevity purposes, we will continue to use the word trademark to describe the different marks mentioned above even though you should know that the using the word trademark, in some instances, might not be technically correct.</p>\r\n<p>Technicalities aside, an underlining issue for all these trademarks, is usage.</p>\r\n<p>Protection of trademarks depends upon, and begins with, &lt;span style="text-decoration: underline"&gt;actual use of the mark in commerce&lt;/span&gt;. Trademark protection is available under the common law from the time that the owner begins to use the trademark in commerce.  However, further protection may be obtained by federally registering the trademark; the fact remains – you get NO protection if you are NOT using the trademark.</p>\r\n<p>The federal registration process is rather straightforward.  Let’s briefly discuss the process of getting your trademark registered through the Patent and Trademark Office (PTO), which is responsible for the federal registration of trademarks.</p>\r\n<p>When an application is received, the PTO reviews it to determine if it meets the minimum requirements for receiving a filing date. If the application meets the filing requirements, the PTO assigns it a serial number and sends the applicant a receipt about two months after filing.  About four months after filing, an examining attorney at the PTO reviews the application and determines whether the mark may be registered.  The examiner will reject an application for several reasons; however, a common ground for refusal is likelihood of confusion between the applicant\'s trademark and existing registered trademark.</p>\r\n<p>If the application is not rejected, then the examiner will approve the trademark for publication in the Official Gazette, a weekly publication of the PTO.  If there is no opposition to the publication, the trademark will finally be considered registered, and the examining attorney will issue a certificate of registration.</p>\r\n<p>Indeed, getting your trademark federally registered is beneficial for several reasons, however, the primary reason to do so is that your trademark will have nation-wide trademark protection.  As opposed to using your trademark without registration, which will limit your trademark protection to your geographical area.  So, your exterminating business with the name Vamanos Pest would more than likely only have trademark protection in your city, maybe county.  It is highly unlikely, in a big state like California, for example, that you could prevent someone in San Francisco from using your trademark, Vamanos Pest, if you are operating the same in San Diego.</p>\r\n<p>As you can imagine, there is a lot more to trademarks than what we have discussed herein.  I only have so much space.  Nevertheless, you should walk away knowing that: 1) trademarks vary in type; 2) you have to use them in commerce; and 3) it’s probably best that you have them federally registered.  If you have any questions regarding trademarks, or if you would like to have a trademark registered, please do not hesitate to contact us.</p>\r\n', 'Trademark - What is it?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '94-revision-2', '', '', '2013-04-24 02:11:37', '2013-04-24 02:11:37', '', 94, 'http://anorgalaw.com/94-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(189, 1, '2012-07-09 13:10:44', '2012-07-09 20:10:44', 'Here are some HR tips for the small business owner -\n\nJOB APPLICATIONS – Many employers do not require prospective employees to submit a job application but instead rely on a person’s resume.  While resumes can be helpful, they should be used in conjunction with an application.  A well-drafted application will elicit useful factual data, and it can also protect an employer by, for example, including an agreement that requires arbitration of all employment related disputes, or also highlight and bring to the prospective employee’s attention, that he or she will be an at-will employment.\n\nEMPLOYEE HANDBOOK – Having a current, legally compliant employee handbook is a must.  A good handbook contains the “rules of engagement”-what the employer expects from its employees and what they can expect from it.  Without a handbook, it is difficult to prove a given policy was in place and understood by your professionals and staff members.\n\nINDEPENDENT CONTRACTORS – Uncertainty over whether a person is an employee or an independent contractor can pose substantial liability for employers.  The money you save on the front end will never earn you enough interest to pay what you will owe on the back end.  Oh, and you will pay.\n\nPERFORMANCE EVALUATIONS – In a busy work environment, it is not at all uncommon for employee evaluations to fall by the wayside entirely.  But employers that don’t conduct regular performance reviews may have difficulty terminating problem employees-especially when there’s a lack of notice regarding problems.\n\nEXIT INTERVIEWS – If an employer chooses to conduct exit interviews, they should be done every time someone leaves the business.  These interviews can be used to help defend a lawsuit if a disgruntled employee decides to sue.  For example, if a departing employee signs an exit interview summary indicating everything was fine, it will be difficult to later contend things were amiss.\n\nTERMINATION – A poorly administered employment termination with little or no documentation can present a serious problem for employers who later seek to show that the action was justified by legitimate, nondiscriminatory reasons.  Always document the reasons for termination\n\nAbiding by these rather straightforward suggestions will ensure that your business, from an HR perspective, operates efficiently, but also help minimize the possibility of legal claims from disgruntled employees.\n', 'Some HR TIPS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '85-revision', '', '', '2012-07-09 13:10:44', '2012-07-09 20:10:44', '', 85, 'http://anorgalaw.com/85-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(190, 1, '2012-07-02 09:55:23', '2012-07-02 16:55:23', '<em>LLCs</em> – Established, for a client, a limited liability company (“LLC”) for the acquisition of a ten (10) unit apartment building.  My office is consistently busy with establishing limited liability companies – maybe it’s a sign the economy and new businesses are coming back.  We are also excited to be establishing an LLC for a new athletic club that will be surfacing sometime later this Fall.\n\n<em>Settlement</em> – I was able to settle the matter of Orellana v. Julio’s Export and Import, Inc., Case Number: BC469855.  We conducted some investigation revealing that the plaintiff’s once tough exterior, was now to starting to demonstrate some cracks.  The client was pleased that we were able to obtain early resolution of this matter.\n\nIn another matter, I was able to settle a dispute that looked like it was destined for a litigation.  My client, who has authorized this statement, delivered some widgets to a company for them to put a shrink-wrap on said widgets.  This company accepted the widgets, did the work, and returned the widgets to my client; however, a significant amount of the widgets were missing from the order.  My client alleged they were properly delivered, the other-side, obviously, alleged the opposite – so, Houston, we have a problem.  The facts of the matter strongly suggested that the company simply lost the widgets, or dropped the ball somehow, and they knew that but, of course, they could not admit to such a costly mistake.  Nevertheless, I was able to work out a deal where both parties were satisfied with the terms and, mostly, importantly, the business relationship between these two salvaged.\n\n<em>Existing Matters</em> – Co-counsel and I are excited that our failure to pay commissions matter, which was being fought on two different fronts, will be consolidated and, ultimately, litigated in one courtroom up North, in Marin County.  This has been a great experience for me to work side-by-side with co-counsel, Clark Rivera – who is also my legal mentor.  He has a high-octane legal mind, and it’s been a beneficial learning experience for me, to be working on this matter. John Wack, et al v. PSI Management Team, Inc., et al, Case Number: CIV1104333.', 'What&#039;s Happening....', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '89-revision', '', '', '2012-07-02 09:55:23', '2012-07-02 16:55:23', '', 89, 'http://anorgalaw.com/89-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(191, 1, '2012-06-29 08:41:33', '2012-06-29 15:41:33', '10. <em>Requiring the employee to sign an unenforceable non-compete agreement as a condition of employment.</em> Why? Because it’s unenforceable and worthless.  Worse, refusing to hire an employee for refusing to sign such an unenforceable agreement exposes you to a wrongful termination lawsuit.\n\n9. <em>Failing to have the employee fill out a meaningful employment application, even if the employee has submitted a resume</em>. Why? Because the resume is the “glam shot” of the employee, and does not always address the specific items of importance to your business.\n\n8. <em>Failing to call and verify references provided by the employee about past employment.</em> Why? Because they may be fake. Surprised. It happens.\n\n7. <em>Failing to confirm the employment offer in writing, with a confirmation that the employment is at-will.</em> Why? Because despite what you actually said in the interview, the employee heard that he was being offered a job for life.  His or hers, not yours.\n\n6. <em>Failing to obtain proof of eligibility to work in the U.S</em>. Why? Because the government is watching. Always. Even when it seems to be fast asleep…and incompetent.\n\n5. <em>Talking instead of listening during the interview.</em> Why? Because you already have the job. You’re trying to find out if the person across from you should have one also. You learn more by listening.\n\n4. <em>Making assumptions about the applicant’s ability based on protected categories (race, gender, pregnancy, national origin, etc.)</em> Why? Because it is totally illegal.  And just beneath you. Don’t be lazy. Ask questions about the job and applicant’s skills and experience, and listen to the answers.\n\n3. <em>Asking about the applicant’s “protected categories” status (race, gender, pregnancy, national origin, etc.)</em> Why? Because it’s also totally illegal, no matter how “cute that accent” is and how much you “respect the passion of people from Latin countries.”\n\n2. <em>Requiring a representation of non-pregnancy</em>. Why? Because it’s none of your business. And because it is illegal.\n\n1. <em>Openly seeking an employee “with benefits.”</em> Why? Hm. Really? Chicago lawyer Samir Zia Chowhan actually posted an ad on Craigslist for a legal secretary whose duties would include “sexual interaction” with him and his partner.  Yes, he was disbarred.', 'Top mistakes that an employer can make during the hiring process.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '86-revision', '', '', '2012-06-29 08:41:33', '2012-06-29 15:41:33', '', 86, 'http://anorgalaw.com/86-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(192, 1, '2012-06-28 11:48:38', '2012-06-28 18:48:38', 'I recently received an email from a client who had these kind words to say:\n\n“Thank you for all you have done so far, it\'s always a pleasure to work with someone as dedicated and efficient as yourself.”\n\n				Ramona O. Novelo – Owner of Sunrise Home Care, Inc\n', 'Client Testimonial ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '185-revision', '', '', '2012-06-28 11:48:38', '2012-06-28 18:48:38', '', 185, 'http://anorgalaw.com/185-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
